inonitriles, mineral catalysis, and environmental consistency."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Aldol condensation: Glycolaldehyde + Acrolein \u2192 4-Aminobutanal", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Montmorillonite-catalyzed aldol/condensation of small aldehydes, followed by amination, yields the four-carbon aminoaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Based on Sutherland et al. (2016, Angew. Chem.) for prebiotic C-C chain extension by aldol reactions on clay surfaces."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyclization: 4-Aminobutanal \u2192 1-Pyrroline", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "calcite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, calcite", "aqueous": true, "other": "wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Spontaneous or clay-induced intramolecular condensation of aminoaldehyde to cyclic imine (1-pyrroline).", "reasoning": "Cited in Sutherland et al. (2018), cyclic imines from aminoaldehydes are favored under surface, dehydration, and mineral-rich conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Strecker Addition to Imine: 1-Pyrroline + HCN \u2192 Pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "neutral pH"}, "mechanism": "HCN attacks the imine carbon, forming aminonitrile; hydrolysis yields the nitrile.", "reasoning": "Follows Strecker-based logic and is referenced by Parker et al. (2011, PNAS); demonstrates convergent creation of the pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile hub."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrothermal r-TCA analog: Pyruvate + Glyoxylate \u2192 \u03b1-Ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "FeS"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite, FeS", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline pH"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed C-C bond formation, akin to r-TCA condensation, generates the C5 dicarboxylic acid.", "reasoning": "Stubbs & Moran (2022, Nat. Ecol. Evol.) describe non-enzymatic TCA analogs, especially under vent-like conditions with FeS minerals."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Transamination: \u03b1-Ketoglutarate + NH3 \u2192 Glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["green rust"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-370K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "green rust", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline, Fe(II)-rich"}, "mechanism": "Amine group transfer from NH3 forms glutamic acid.", "reasoning": "Stubbs & Moran (2020, 2022) and Parker et al. (2021, PNAS) support this as a robust prebiotic route to amino acids via hydrothermal proto-metabolism."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Dehydrogenation: Glutamate \u2192 P5C", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "FeS"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-360K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, FeS", "aqueous": true, "other": "oscillating pH"}, "mechanism": "Partial oxidation removes two H atoms, forming \u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylate.", "reasoning": "Stubbs & Moran (2020, Nat. Ecol. Evol.) and Sutherland et al. (2018) discuss P5C as the convergent intermediate in both metabolism-first and systems-first models; ring closure is mineral-facilitated."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Reduction: P5C \u2192 L-Proline", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["FeS", "green rust"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-340K", "pres